The Rct and Rs parameters for the flexible devices were calculated from the Nyquist plots (Fig. 8
                        ). For the GOcom-SC and GOLIB-SC devices, Fig. 8a-8b, the respective Rct/Rs values were 0.92 Ω / 18.11 Ω and 0.54 Ω / 20.83 Ω. These results indicate that the use of commercial graphite as a precursor for GO improves the Rct and Rs parameters by approximately 70 % and 15 %, respectively, compared to LIB-derived graphite. On the other hand, the devices incorporating graphene quantum dots (Fig. 8c and d), GOcom+GQDscom-SC and GOLIB+GQDsLIB-SC, exhibited significantly lower Rct and Rs values, reflecting an improvement in the electrical conductivity of the materials. The Rct/Rs values for these devices were 0.12 Ω/3.56 Ω and 0.23 Ω/4.38 Ω, respectively. Notably, the GOcom+GQDs-SC device demonstrated an improvement in conductivity, with reductions in Rct and Rs of approximately 91 % and 23 %, respectively. The incorporation of GQDs in the GOcom-SC and GOLIB-SC devices had a significant impact. The Rct and Rs parameters improved significantly, with enhancements of 660 %/410 % for GOcom+GQDscom-SC and 134 % / 375 % for GOLIB+GQDsLIB-SC. These findings suggest that the presence of GQDs not only enhances the redox behavior of the electrodes but also improves surface conductivity, thereby reducing energy losses and increasing the energy storage capabilities of the materials. In general, incorporating GQDs enhanced the electrochemical performance of flexible energy storage devices, providing a pathway for the development of more efficient and reliable supercapacitors. In order to compare our results with the literature Table 2
                         was elaborated.
